observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following to management:

1. The OIC-Mun. Economic Ent. Dev’t. Office exert effort in retrieving data and records on the accounts which do not show ending balances, in order to determine the status of such and facilitate proper recording;

2.	The MEEDO, together with the Accounting Office, prepare schedules of payment per account to determine the correct balances of Finance Lease Receivable, Deferred Finance Lease Revenue and Lease Revenue;

3.	The Municipal Engineer and Municipal Assessor assist in identifying the cost of the road networks within the USWAG Village;

4.	The Sangguniang Bayan determine the interest rate to which the value of Residential Lots is to be discounted. Such will be necessary in the computation of the correct amount of Lease Revenue to be recognized; and

5.	The Municipal Accountant make the necessary correcting journal entries to reflect the correct balances of the appropriate accounts and to furnish the Auditor a copy of the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) taking up the adjustments.

We recommended the following to management:


1.    Adopt a system that will ensure close monitoring of the execution of all PPAs to warrant their efficient and timely completion in order to deliver the desirable socio-economic and environmental development due to the public;

2.    Ensure that proposed programs/projects are feasible and implementation ready; and

3.    Coordinate with the respective Barangay Officials to ensure that appropriations for their counterpart are provided in their Annual Budget and transfer to the LGU the required amount once the fund is available for its timely implementation.


1.    Continue the review of the previous years’ AIPs in order to determine unimplemented PPAs which caused the huge bank balance and identify the need and feasibility of such;

2.    Fast-track the implementation of PPAs by ensuring that projects are awarded to contractors/bidders who have the necessary manpower and resources to implement awarded projects on time;

3.    For projects already awarded but not yet started/completed, determine whether there are reasons to justify the delay otherwise, impose liquidated damages and/or the possibility to rescind the contract; and 

4.    In event that such are no longer feasible, conduct consultations with stakeholders in identifying development projects to be funded out of the available funds of the 20% DF to achieve optimum utilization.

We recommend the following to management:

The Local Finance Committee re-evaluate the target settings by considering the past years’ actual collections in the preparation of the budget for the succeeding year to come up with a viable and realistic budget;

The Municipal Treasurer’s Office (MTO), as the collecting arms of the municipality, Municipal Economic Enterprise Development Office (MEEDO), as the office in-charge of the municipality’s sand and gravel operations, and the Mahayag Municipal Hospital (MMH) to improve their operation and collection efficiency where the target revenue and receipts during the year were missed;

xxx

Recommendation

We recommended the management to require the following:
The Liquidating Officer to submit the RCDs, copies of the ORs and the validated deposit slips related to these unrecorded collections for CY 2024;
The Municipal Treasurer to ensure compliance with the procedures  in Chapter 3, Volume I of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002 ;
The Municipal Treasurer and the Liquidating Officer coordinate with the Municipal Accountant for purposes of reconciliation, review of records and make necessary adjustment to correct the noted deficiencies in order to have an updated and correct balances; and
The Local Chief Executive (LCE) ensure that the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer reconcile regularly their respective cash records to detect instantly any errors made in the process.

Recommendation

We recommended the management the following:
Maintain the practice of sending demand letters to employees with outstanding cash advances requiring them to settle unliquidated CAs and do the same on a regular basis;
Require the Municipal Accountant to monitor outstanding cash advances of every official & employee and report the status of their liquidations to the Local Chief Executive on a regular basis for appropriate action by the latter;
For unliquidated cash advances of personnel who are still in active service and after receiving the demand letters, still failed to settle their obligation nor made an appropriate justification, immediately withhold their salaries or any amount due them until balances have been fully settled;
Make appropriate disclosures in the Notes to FS on the actual status of unliquidated cash advances for confidential fund, particularly those granted prior to the effectivity of COA-DBM JC 2015-01; and
Initiate action to recover unsettled CAs of personnel who were already separated from service upon failure by the latter to respond to demand letters.

We recommended the following to management:

1.    MEEDO to:

Send demand letter to delinquent lot owners to settle their accounts;
Together with concerned LGU Officers, conduct dialogues with the delinquent lot owners in order to arrive at an agreeable payment scheme to settle their accounts;
Send periodic statement of accounts/billing to buyers;
Negotiate with buyers who were granted 2 lots, especially those who have not yet paid fully their balances, in order to consolidate all their previous payments to 1 lot and open the 2nd lot for new application;
Facilitate the processing for the titling of fully paid lots;
Require those who assume lots from the first buyers to pay the required 15% transfer fee;
Maintain individual folders for each account in order to organize all documents relative to such account;
Prepare a draft contract for the terms and conditions for the review and approval by the Sangguniang Bayan. Thereafter, the LGU and buyers must enter into the said contract;
Furnish the monthly billing for locally-employed buyers to the Accounting Office so that proper salary deduction shall be made; and
Submit to the Accounting Office a copy of the Outstanding Balances of pertaining to these account for proper recording of Finance Lease Receivable.

2.    The accounting unit, being the one to prepare the payroll, ensure that the correct amount of monthly due for these lots are actually deducted from salaries of locally employed buyers;

3.    The Municipal Accountant recognize the unpaid rentals and its penalties, if applicable, in the books of the Municipality as receivable and income, in order to fairly present the financial statements of the municipality; and

4.    The Sangguniang Bayan consider amending the Guidelines and Policies on the Distribution, Selling Price and Term of Payment of the Residential Lots of USWAG VILLAGE of Mahayag, Zamboanga del Sur and add penal provisions for non-payment of fees on time by stallholders which may include imposition of penalties and rescission of contracts.

We recommended the following to management: 

1.    Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

Cause the immediate full liquidation of outstanding fund transfers received from National Government Agencies and strictly adhere to the provisions of Section 6 of COA Circular No. 94-013 dated December 13, 1994 and Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;

Collate records to ensure that all unspent balances of fund transfers for completed projects irrespective of source agency be returned;

Exert effort in retrieving records and information to identify the details of fund transfers with outstanding balance maintained under common account, “Consolidated”, and return to source agency if applicable. Otherwise, make recommendation to the Local Chief Executive and Sangguniang Bayan to revert such fund to the General Fund to be used for other social services; and

2.    Offices in charge of the implementation for each fund transfer fast track the implementation of the fund transfers since the resources are readily available in order not to deprive the Municipality of the benefits out of the PPA.

We recommended that:

1.	The MDRRMO, MDRRMC and Municipal Budget Officer determine the appropriate allotment class for LDRRM PPAs in the preparation of the LDRRMFIP and Annual Budget;

2.	Management refrain from passing resolutions to treat unexpended balance of appropriations at year end as continuing appropriations, except for capital outlay;

3.	The Municipal Budget Officer, correct and maintain the necessary registries for the LDRRM-CO continuing appropriations; and

4.	The Municipal Accountant make the necessary journal entries to reflect the correct balance for the Trust Liabilities – Disaster Risk Reduction and Management account. The QRF and LDRRMF-MOOE unexpended/unobligated balances be transferred to the Trust Fund while the LDRRMF for CO is to be made continuing in the General Fund until the projects funded therefore are completed.

We recommend the following to management:

The Local Finance Committee re-evaluate the target settings by considering the past years’ actual collections in the preparation of the budget for the succeeding year to come up with a viable and realistic budget;

The Municipal Treasurer’s Office (MTO), as the collecting arms of the municipality, Municipal Economic Enterprise Development Office (MEEDO), as the office in-charge of the municipality’s sand and gravel operations, and the Mahayag Municipal Hospital (MMH) to improve their operation and collection efficiency where the target revenue and receipts during the year were missed;

The Municipal Engineering Office to fast track the implementation of rechanneling of the Salug River, in order to protect the constituents from dangers of flooding, soil erosion, devastation of vegetation and damage to properties, and to continue the LGUs quarry operations as this is the 2nd largest source of the LGU’s internal income.

We recommend that:

Management conduct dialogues with the delinquent stallholders in order to arrive at an agreeable payment scheme to settle their accounts;

Management cause the closure of the establishments, the revocation of the lease contracts and ejection in case of failure to fully settle their accounts within the agreed period and apply the administrative and/or judicial actions as enumerated in Section 174 of RA 7160 in order to recover the amount due; and

The Sangguniang Bayan consider amending The Revised Economic Enterprise Code of the Municipality of Mahayag, Zamboanga del Sur to add penal provisions for non-payment of fees on time by stallholders which may include imposition of penalties, temporary closure, and revocation of contract and ejection;

The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Economic Enterprise and Development Office Head periodically provide the Municipal Accountant with the List of Delinquent Market Stallholders with amount due and penalties to facilitate timely recording of accrued rental income; and

The Municipal Accountant to recognize the unpaid rentals and its penalties, if applicable, in the books of the Municipality as receivable and income, in order to fairly present the financial statements of the municipality.

We recommend that management require:

The inventory committee to prepare and submit the approved PIP to the Office of the Auditor at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory count and perform the count on all PPE items as indicated in the PIP;

The Municipal Accountant and GSO Designate:

Continuously reconcile the result of the physical count with the property and accounting records;

Maintain and update the PPELC for each category of assets and RPLC for land, and PC, respectively; and

The Municipal Accountant to submit breakdown of the derecognized PPE showing individual costs for each item.

We recommend that management direct the Municipal Accountant to
Review the composition of the financial liabilities and make appropriate entry to close the accounts that existed due to overstatement, understatement and erroneous entries;

Send confirmation letter to the supposed suppliers to verify the existence of the obligations and secure sufficient evidence to support the validity of the claims and payment of the accounts;

Revert to the Unappropriated Surplus of the General Fund those that proved to be with no valid claims; and

Conduct periodic review and monitoring of the payable accounts so that this account will consist only of valid claims against the LGU.

We recommended the following to management:

The LCE direct the HRMO to formulate uniform policy and procedures in engaging and managing COS and JO personnel taking into consideration the issuances of Civil Service Commission as to the appropriate forms and types of contracts and classification of personnel; and internal controls to ensure that they are performing the required task, reporting to the official station, and bases of assigning wage rates;

The Sangguniang Bayan, upon review and deliberation, institutionalize the policy and procedures in engaging and managing COS and JO personnel, as prepared by the HRMO, by legislating it into an ordinance;

Refrain from engaging Contract of Services from those who are not consultants, learning service providers or technical experts to undertake special projects or jobs within a specific period; and assigning of higher rates for those who are performing routine, clerical, administrative and other support services;

Use appropriate forms or type of contracts for those who are support services personnel and should equally assign standard wage rates;

Require all COS and JO personnel to register their attendance in the Biometric Machine, especially those whose official station is within or near the Municipal Hall where the Biometric Machines are located. Also, assign responsible personnel to be in charge of the Logbook who shall certify or affix his initials for each manual entries in the DTRs;

Exemptions to register in the Biometrics must be granted only to those whose official stations are located far away from the Municipal Hall. The LGU must prioritize the provision of Biometric Machines to these offices, otherwise, a Logbook must be maintained where they may record their attendance; and

The HRMO to carry out a periodic orientation/reorientation for COS and JO personnel so that the basic office rules and regulations, the use of travel order and the requirement of certificate of appearance, format and preparation of quantifiable accomplishment reports, roles and responsibilities of outsourced personnel, reporting lines or supervisory authority, mode or processes of separation/termination of contract shall be clear to them.

2.9 We recommended that:
2.9.1 Management conduct dialogues with the delinquent stallholders in order to arrive at an agreeable payment scheme to settle their accounts;
2.9.2 Management cause the closure of the establishments, the revocation of the lease contracts and ejection in case of failure to fully settle their accounts within the agreed period and apply the administrative and/or judicial actions as enumerated in Section 174 of RA 7160 in order to recover the amount due;
2.9.3 The Sangguniang Bayan consider amending The Revised Economic Enterprise Code of the Municipality of Mahayag, Zamboanga del Sur to add penal provisions for non-payment of fees on time by stallholders which may include imposition of penalties, temporary closure, and revocation of contract and ejection;
2.9.4 The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Economic Enterprise and Development Office Head periodically provide the Municipal Accountant with the List of Delinquent Market Stallholders with amount due and penalties to facilitate timely recording of accrued rental income; and
2.9.5 The Municipal Accountant recognize the unpaid rentals and its penalties, if applicable, in the books of the Municipality as receivable and income, in order to fairly present the financial statements of the municipality.

3.7 We recommended that the management:
3.7.1 Strictly enforce liquidation of the outstanding CAs of the Municipal officials and employees who are still in active service by sending demand letters requiring submission of the liquidation documents for the settlement of their accounts;
3.7.2 If no settlement is received, enforce the provisions of the COA Circular on the liquidation of CAs, particularly the withholding of salaries of the accountable officers who fail to liquidate their CAs within the prescribed period;
3.7.3 Exert earnest effort in locating the officials and employees whose term has ended, retired or resigned, and require settlement/refund of the CAs; and
3.7.4 Require the accounting office to devise an effective monitoring system for the grant and liquidation of CAs to avoid accumulation of outstanding receivables.

We recommended that Management:

Identify the intended beneficiaries and distribute the remaining welfare goods that are fit for human consumption as soon as possible;

Ensure that the expiration dates of the acquired welfare goods be at least six months from date of delivery; 

Consider the quantity of the undistributed welfare goods at a given time to determine the re-order point to avoid over stocking;

Observe proper handling and storage of welfare goods to safeguard against any loss, infestation of pest and insects, spoilage and or wastage; and

For expired goods, exert efforts to have the goods be replaced and submit justification for such an occurrence.

We recommended the following: 

Enforce full liquidation of cash advances within the reglementary period as provided under COA Circular No.97-002; 
No subsequent cash advance should be granted pending liquidation of previous cash advances;
Demand the concerned officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances to effect immediate settlement, otherwise, sanction for non-settlement as provided for in paragraph 9.1 of COA Circular No. 2012-004 be enforced, if warranted; and 
File for a request of write-off on dormant accounts as provided for in COA Circular Circular No. 2016-005.

